{"id":"woodward-avenue","generatedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z","designation":"All-American Road","parkCode":null,"source":{"roadArticle":"M-1 (Michigan highway)","revisionId":1355194740,"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Woodward_Avenue"},"attribution":{"license":"CC BY-SA 4.0","licenseUrl":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/","articleUrl":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Woodward_Avenue","text":"Route, junction, and history details adapted from the Wikipedia article \"M-1 (Michigan highway)\", by Wikipedia contributors, licensed under CC BY-SA 4.0."},"sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia","src":"wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Woodward_Avenue","revisionId":1355194740,"retrievedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z"},{"name":"Federal Highway Administration — National Scenic Byways","src":"fhwa","url":"https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/byways","retrievedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z"},{"name":"OpenStreetMap contributors (ODbL)","src":"osm","url":"https://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright","retrievedAt":"2026-07-11T07:11:33.093Z"}],"endpoints":{"from":"Detroit, MI","to":"Bloomfield Township, MI","via":["Highland Park, MI","Royal Oak, MI"]},"itinerary":[{"seq":1,"place":"Detroit","state":"MI","kind":"terminus","mileFromStart":0,"toNextMi":5.1,"note":"The drive begins here","control":["Adams AvenueWoodward Avenue south","Port Huron"],"lat":42.37295,"lng":-83.0751,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":2,"place":"Highland Park","state":"MI","kind":"town","mileFromStart":5.1,"toNextMi":5.6,"note":"Junction toward M-8 (Davison Freeway)","control":["M-8 (Davison Freeway)"],"lat":42.40551,"lng":-83.097,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":3,"place":"Royal Oak","state":"MI","kind":"town","mileFromStart":10.7,"toNextMi":10.8,"note":"Junction toward Lansing & Port Huron","control":["Lansing","Port Huron","Detroit Zoo"],"lat":42.41712,"lng":-83.10482,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":4,"place":"Bloomfield Township","state":"MI","kind":"terminus","mileFromStart":21.5,"toNextMi":null,"note":"The drive ends here","control":["BL I-75 (Square Lake Road east","Woodward Avenue north)","Bus. US 24 (Square Lake Road west","Woodward Avenue north)"],"lat":null,"lng":null,"src":"wikipedia"}],"history":{"paragraphs":["In 1701, the first transportation routes through what became the state of Michigan were the lakes, rivers and Indian trails. One of these, the Saginaw Trail, followed what is now Woodward Avenue from the Detroit area north to Saginaw, where it connected with the Mackinaw Trail north to the Straits of Mackinac. The Town of Detroit[b] created 120-foot-wide (37 m) rights-of-way for the principal streets of the city in 1805. This street plan was devised by Augustus Woodward and others following a devastating fire in Detroit, with a mandate from the territorial governor to improve on the previous plan. Two of these principal streets were established by the territorial government on September 18, 1805, as \"permanent public roads, avenues or highways\", one of which was to run along the modern routing of Woodward Avenue. The wide avenues, in emulation of the street plan for Washington, DC, were intended to make Detroit look like the \"Paris of the West\".","Augustus Woodward was a judge in the Michigan Territory appointed by his friend, President Thomas Jefferson. He was also a colonel in the territorial militia and a president of one of Detroit's first banks. Woodward named the street for himself, responding whimsically to the resulting criticism: \"Not so. The avenue is named Woodward because it runs wood-ward, toward the woods.\"[c] Other proposals for names included Court House Street or Market Street. For a time, one section was named Congress Street, Witherell Street, Saginaw Road or Saginaw Turnpike, with another section dubbed Pontiac Road. Unlike these other monikers, the avenue retained the judge's name.","Detroit was incorporated in 1815, and the initial roadway to connect Detroit north to Pontiac along the Saginaw Trail was started in 1817; this was a corduroy road built by laying down logs and filling in the gaps with clay or sand. The territorial legislature authorized a survey of the roadway to Pontiac on December 7, 1818, and the route was approved by Governor Lewis Cass on December 15, 1819, the first to be done in the future state. The Michigan Legislature authorized the construction of a private plank road with tolls to connect Detroit with Pontiac in 1848. By the next year, 16-foot-wide (4.9 m) and 3-inch-thick (7.6 cm) oak planks were laid along the road between the two communities. Tolls were one cent per mile (0.62 ¢/km) for vehicles and two cents per mile (1.2 ¢/km) for a herd of cattle. Tolls along some segments of Woodward Avenue remained in place as late as 1908.","The first automobile in Detroit was driven by Charles Brady King along Woodward Avenue on March 3, 1896, a few weeks before Henry Ford drove his first car in the city. In 1909, the first mile (1.6 km) of concrete roadway in the country was paved between 6 and 7 Mile roads at a cost of $14,000 (equivalent to $349,000 in 2024)."],"sourceSection":"History","src":"wikipedia"},"highlights":[{"n":"Detroit","d":"The drive begins here","q":"Detroit","lat":42.33166667,"lng":-83.04583333,"src":"wikipedia"}],"references":[{"n":1,"text":"Another highway, M-22 in Northern Michigan has also been the subject of sign theft with different methods used to deter sign removal.","url":""},{"n":2,"text":"Detroit was incorporated as a town in 1802 by the government of the Northwest Territory before incorporation and reincorporation as a city by the Michigan Territory in 1806 and 1815.","url":""},{"n":3,"text":"Woodward used other similar word plays to explain street names, according to George Catlin, a Detroit historian. \"Atwater Street, the Judge said, was not named for Reuben Atwater, but because it was literally 'at water,' being on the riverfront\".","url":""},{"n":4,"text":"Since July 1, 1974, the Department of Street Railways has been renamed the Detroit Department of Transportation, the agency responsible for the city's bus system. That bus system was started in 1925 as a feeder network to serve the streetcar lines.","url":""},{"n":5,"text":"Michigan Department of Transportation (2021). Next Generation PR Finder (Map). Michigan Department of Transportation. Retrieved October 11, 2021.","url":"https://mdotgis.state.mi.us/portal/apps/webappviewer/index.html?id=c3aa2462a1e24e37a33184a33e5976aa"},{"n":6,"text":"Michigan Legislature (1915) [enacted May 13, 1913]. \"Chapter 91: State Reward Trunk Line Highways\". In Shields, Edmund C.; Black, Cyrenius P. & Broomfield, Archibald (eds.). The Compiled Laws of the State of Michigan. Vol. 1. Lansing, Michigan: Wynkoop, Hallenbeck, Crawford. pp. ","url":"https://books.google.com/books?id=7kXiAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA1868"},{"n":7,"text":"Michigan Department of Transportation (2023). National Functional Classification (Map). Michigan Department of Transportation. Archived from the original on July 12, 2023. Retrieved July 18, 2023.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20230712034121/https://www.mcgi.state.mi.us/nfc/"},{"n":8,"text":"Michigan Department of Transportation (2023). Traffic AADT Map (Map). Michigan Department of Transportation. Retrieved July 18, 2023.","url":"https://mdot.maps.arcgis.com/apps/webappviewer/index.html?id=50dd462048fd4971998567699698f285"}],"routeLine":[[42.37295,-83.0751],[42.37245,-83.07465],[42.37191,-83.07429],[42.37124,-83.07385],[42.37048,-83.07332],[42.36983,-83.07295],[42.36841,-83.0721],[42.36901,-83.07261],[42.36572,-83.07035],[42.36633,-83.07085],[42.36417,-83.06921],[42.36146,-83.06738],[42.35912,-83.06584],[42.35766,-83.06482],[42.35436,-83.06273],[42.35104,-83.06034],[42.34959,-83.05936],[42.35012,-83.05972],[42.34435,-83.05585],[42.34156,-83.05408],[42.341,-83.05371],[42.34041,-83.05326],[42.34125,-83.0537],[42.34227,-83.05436],[42.34163,-83.05412],[42.33963,-83.05265],[42.33903,-83.05215],[42.33841,-83.05173],[42.33777,-83.05129],[42.3371,-83.05083],[42